CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification scoring  protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent 3D workstation as ordered by the treating  provider and reviewed by the radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according  to the Agatston-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.      COMPARISON: Cardiac CT from 11/17/2009. Chest CT from 3/10/2021 and studies back to 10/12/2016    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 9  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 9  Percentile rank: 50 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for coronary artery disease  with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex is 57%.    OTHER FINDINGS: Stable 10 mm left upper lobe peribronchial nodule (2/65) since March 2021 but  increased over studies back to at least October 2016. Slowly growing now 7 mm rather than 5 mm (in  2016) left lower lobe endobronchial nodule (2/113). Stable 4 mm left lower lobe nodule (2/103).  Stable 5 mm right lower lobe nodule (2/85). Stable 3 mm right middle lobe nodule (2/122). Severe  hepatic steatosis. Colonic diverticulosis. Bilateral gynecomastia with reduction mammoplasty.     IMPRESSION:    1. The observed coronary calcium score of 9 is at percentile rank 50.  2. Slowly growing left upper lobe and left lower lobe peribronchial/endobronchial nodules over  studies back to 2016, concerning for indolent carcinoid tumors. Other lung nodules are stable.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification scoring  protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent 3D workstation as ordered by the treating  provider and reviewed by the radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according  to the Agatston-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: No similar prior studies are available for comparison at the time of interpretation.    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 375  Circumflex coronary artery: 154  Right coronary artery: 1    Agatston score: 529  Percentile rank: 99 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for coronary artery disease  with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex is 26%.    OTHER FINDINGS: Extensive calcification of the aortic valve leaflets. No aneurysm of the visualized  thoracic aorta. The main pulmonary artery is enlarged measuring approximately 32 mm, nonspecific  finding that can be seen in the setting of pulmonary hypertension. Small hiatal hernia and patulous  esophagus. Partially imaged prominent mediastinal lymph nodes that may be reactive. Bilateral  bronchial wall thickening with associated groundglass opacities and centrilobular/tree-in-bud  nodules in the right middle lobe, left lower lobe, and lingula, compatible with  bronchiolitis/bronchopneumonia. No consolidation in the visualized lung parenchyma.    IMPRESSION:    The observed coronary calcium score of 529 is at percentile rank 99.    Aortic valve leaflet calcification is in keeping with reported bicuspid aortic valve and aortic  valve stenosis.    Bronchitis and bronchiolitis with possible superimposed bronchopneumonia may be related to  aspiration in the setting of small hiatal hernia and patulous esophagus.ADDENDUM:    Calculated aortic valve calcium score of 891. Original report text remains unchanged.

Chest_Xray_report: EXAM:  DX CHEST 1 VIEW    COMPARISON:  Chest radiograph 9/30/2021, 9/29/2021, 9/28/2021    IMPRESSION:  Extubation and removal of enteric tube. Left IJ central venous  catheter with tip at the right atrium. Right  IJ Swan-Ganz catheter tip in the proximal right pulmonary artery. Stable  position of the bilateral and mediastinal chest tubes/drains. Epicardial pacer  wires in place.    No measurable pneumothorax. Small pleural effusions, left greater than right.  Mild increase in interstitial opacities associated with pulmonary edema. Left  intracardiac opacity probably represents atelectasis.    Postsurgical changes of median median sternotomy for aortic valve replacement,  CABG, and left atrial appendage clipping. Small postoperative pneumomediastinum.  Nondisplaced median sternotomy wires. Surgical clips overlie the midline.
CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST    COMPARISON: No comparisons available    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CTA of the heart with contrast enhancement and with 3D  reconstructions.     Coronary artery findings:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 200  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 824  Circumflex coronary artery: 154  Right coronary artery: 1981    Agatston score: 3159  Percentile rank: 99th % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    Image degradation by cardiac motion and blooming artifact from calcific  atherosclerotic plaque. Four-vessel calcific atherosclerotic plaque.    There is a right dominant system.  Left main: Predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque  LAD: Mixed calcified and noncalcified atherosclerotic plaque involving the  proximal and mid LAD.  L Circumflex: Few scattered predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque  RCA: Diffuse multifocal atherosclerotic plaque. Focus of mixed atherosclerotic  plaque involving the mid to distal RCA (series 5, image 242-251).    Aorta: Normal caliber aorta.     LV:  LV Ejection Fraction: 50%   LV End Diastolic Volume: 140 mL  LV End Systolic Volume:  71 mL    RV: Normal size and function.    Right Atrium: Borderline enlarged.  Left Atrium: Enlarged; LA AP diameter measures 50 mm.    Myocardium: Normal myocardial thickness.  Valves: Aortic valve leaflet calcifications. There is diminished aortic leaflet  excursion compatible with history of aortic stenosis.  Septa: Normal  Pulmonary arteries: There is no pulmonary embolism. The main pulmonary artery is  dilated measuring up to 3.3 cm.  There are four pulmonary veins with separate ostia. There is no thrombus in the  left atrial appendage.    Pericardium: Small pericardial effusion.      Non-cardiac findings: Bilateral pleural effusions with associated atelectasis.  Cholecystectomy. Anasarca.     This exam was read jointly with Dr. Amy Pollak.     IMPRESSION:    1. No evidence of pulmonary embolism.  2. Normal LV size with low-normal/mildly diminished function. LVEF 50%   3. Agatston coronary calcium score of 3159. This places the patient in the 99th  percentile.  4. Right dominant coronary system. Diffuse four-vessel coronary artery  atherosclerotic plaque. The degree of calcification precludes optimal assessment  for stenosis. CAD RADS: N  5. Calcified aortic valve leaflets with diminished leaflet excursion compatible  with history of aortic stenosis.  6. Normal right ventricular chamber size and systolic function.  7. Small bilateral pleural effusions and small pericardial effusion.

Chest_Xray_report: EXAM:  DX CHEST AP OR PA AND LATERAL 2 VIEWS    COMPARISON:  2/24/2020.    IMPRESSION:  Mild new patchy bilateral parenchymal opacities, including overlying  the third left anterior rib and right sixth anterior and ninth posterior rib  confluence. Findings could represent sequela of mild infectious/inflammatory  airways process. Follow-up to clearing with PA and lateral views of the chest  recommended. If abnormalities persist then further evaluation with CT chest  recommended. No pneumothorax, edema or pleural effusion is seen. Cardiac  silhouette is not enlarged. Aortic contours are stable. Bones demonstrate mild  degenerative changes of the spine.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: None    TECHNIQUE: Pre-contrast coronary calcium scoring was performed with prospective  ECG-gating.     3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and  rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on a  workstation with 3D capabilities.    COMPARISON: CT chest angiogram September 11, 2019    CORONARY FINDINGS:   Study somewhat limited secondary to motion, particularly left main and LAD near  the bifurcation.    Normal coronary anatomy and courses. Coronary circulation is Right dominant.    Calcium Score: Left main = zero; Left anterior descending = zero; Circumflex =  zero; Right =zero  Total score: zero    Left main coronary artery: Normal, no disease; no stenosis.    Left anterior descending coronary artery system: Somewhat limited, especially  secondary to motion along the first diagonal.    Left circumflex coronary artery: Normal proximal circumflex, with small caliber  branches tapering distally.    Right coronary artery: Normal with normal posterior descending branch, no  disease; no stenosis.    Accounting for limitation of the study, no definite dissection identified.    OTHER FINDINGS:   visualized lungs demonstrate left pneumonectomy and numerous nodules within the  hyperexpanded right lung compatible with metastasis. These findings are better  assessed on the CT angiogram 9/11/2019.    IMPRESSION:      Study somewhat limited by motion artifact, however without significant stenosis  or myocardial hypoperfusion to suggest infarct. No findings of coronary  calcifications with coronary calcium score of 0.    Lung metastasis, better evaluated on prior CT 9/11/2019..

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery  calcification scoring protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent  3D workstation as ordered by the treating provider and reviewed by the  radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 0  Percentile rank: 0-62% in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is 38%.    OTHER FINDINGS: Study somewhat degraded by some respiratory motion, there are  several scattered pulmonary nodules, most of them are benign calcified  granulomas however some are indeterminate, noncalcified for example subpleural 5  mm right upper lobe nodule, solid, series 3 image 18, probably along the minor  fissure. 2 mm subpleural left lower lobe nodule, series 3 image 51. Otherwise  visualized portions of the lungs appear clear. Multiple calcified hilar and  lower mediastinal lymph nodes consistent with old granulomatous disease. There  is some dilatation of the aortic root difficult to further characterize on this  noncontrast exam, at the sinuses of Valsalva the aorta appears to measure up to  48 mm in diameter. No pericardial thickening or pericardial effusion. Limited  evaluation of the upper abdomen is unremarkable.     IMPRESSION:  The observed coronary calcium score of 0 is at percentile rank : 0-62%. 62% of  patients in an age, gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated  with a high negative predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial  infarction and cardiac related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or  exceeding 99%.    Aneurysmal dilatation of the aortic root, at the sinuses of Valsalva, the aorta  measures up to 48 mm in diameter.    Scattered small solid pulmonary nodules measuring up to 5 mm, probably  noncalcified granulomas given other findings of old granulomatous disease;  however, if patient is high risk a follow-up CT can be performed in 12 months to  confirm stability.

Dendriform pulmonary ossification.

COMPARISON: Chest CT, 4/22/2011    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 396  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 193  Circumflex coronary artery: 64  Right coronary artery: 2000    Agatston score: 2653  Percentile rank: 94% in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is 84%.    OTHER FINDINGS: Some bibasilar atelectasis noted, areas of air trapping,  bronchial wall thickening suggestive of some underlying airways disease and  centrilobular emphysema. No significant pleural pericardial effusion is seen.  Fusiform dilatation of the ascending aorta measures up to approximately 45 mm in  diameter. Central pulmonary arteries are prominent measuring up to 31 mm  suggestive of some pulmonary hypertension. Prominent cardiac fat pad noted.  Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen is unremarkable. No lytic or blastic  osseous lesions are seen. Some prominent osteophytes noted in the lower thoracic  spine.     IMPRESSION:  The observed coronary calcium score of 2653 is at percentile rank: 94%.    The degree of coronary calcium as such that contrast-enhanced CT angiography of  the coronary arteries was felt to probably be of limited value due to extensive  blooming artifact throughout the mid to distal RCA, distal left main and  proximal LAD. The degree of atherosclerotic disease in the coronary arteries in  conjunction with the patient's history probably warrants catheter angiography.  As such, the exam was terminated prior to giving intravenous contrast.    Aneurysmal dilatation of ascending aorta up to 45 mm noted.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM TRIPLE RULE OUT WITH IV CONTRAST, CT CARDIAC SCORING  WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    ECG-gated CT angiogram of the chest with IV contrast done according to the acute  chest pain protocol, including independent workstation 3D reformations.        COMPARISON:  No prior cross-sectional imaging of the chest is available at this  time. PA and lateral chest radiographs 01/23/2019.    FINDINGS:    PULMONARY ARTERIES:  Negative for acute pulmonary embolism. Nondilated main pulmonary arteries.    THORACIC AORTA:   Nonaneurysmal. Negative for intramural hematoma, dissection, or penetrating  atherosclerotic ulcer. Minimal atherosclerotic plaque of the aortic arch and  descending thoracic aorta. Left-sided aortic arch with normal variant direct  origin of the left vertebral artery.    CORONARY CALCIUM CT:  Noncontrast CT scan of the heart was done for coronary artery calcification  scoring.  The examination is positive and shows definite calcium deposits which  are diagnostic of atherosclerotic disease.        The calcium score is 3278. This amount of calcifications is greater than  expected and places the patient at the 99th percentile for amount of  calcification when compared to an age and gender-matched peer group. Calcium is  present in the left main, left anterior descending, left circumflex, and right  coronary arteries.    CORONARY CTA:  Image quality: Degraded by diffuse coronary artery calcification and cardiac  pulsation artifact despite maximum intravenous Lopressor administration per  radiology protocol. Heart rate average is 78.  Origins/course: Normal.  Dominance: Right.  Left Main Coronary: Patent. Predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque in  the distal segment immediately proximal to the bifurcation results in less than  50% luminal stenosis.  Left Anterior Descending: Patent. Diffuse predominantly calcified  atherosclerotic plaque in all segments beginning at the origin. Calcification  significantly degrades evaluation for luminal stenosis.  Left Circumflex: Patent. Diffuse predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque  in all segments significantly degrades evaluation for luminal stenosis. Distal  segment terminates as a dominant second obtuse marginal branch.  Right Coronary: Patent. No luminal stenosis of the origin.  Otherwise, diffuse  predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque in all segments significantly  degrades evaluation for luminal stenosis.    OTHER CARDIOVASCULAR FINDINGS:  No resting left ventricular myocardial perfusion defect. Normal biventricular  myocardial thickness, chamber size, and systolic function by qualitative  assessment. Evaluation of the right atrium is degraded by mixing of opacified  blood from the SVC and unopacified blood from the IVC.    Mild thickening and minimal calcification of the aortic valve cusps.    ADDITIONAL FINDINGS:   Bilateral anterior posterior cervical, subpectoral, axillary, mediastinal, and  hilar lymphadenopathy. Lymphadenopathy is greatest in the axillary and  subpectoral chains. Examples: Right subpectoral lymph node, 66 mm x 28 mm  (series 5, image 27). Subcarinal lymph node, 34 mm x 20 mm (series 5, image  124). Right hilar lymph node 38 mm x 23 mm (series 5, image 104).    Mild residual thymus/thymic hyperplasia.    Trace simple inferior pericardial effusion.     Trace simple layering bilateral pleural effusions.    Diffuse bronchial wall thickening. Nodular noncavitary peribronchovascular  consolidation and adjacent groundglass opacities in all segments of the right  upper lobe greatest in the posterior segment. Multifocal and bilateral upper  lobe and centrilobular and tree-in-bud distribution predominant solid and  groundglass micronodularity also greatest in the right upper lobe.    Cortical and intramedullary osseous sclerotic lesion without soft tissue mass or  pathologic fracture in the left glenoid (series 5, image 11). Mild symmetric  gynecomastia. Mild dependent subcutaneous body wall edema.    CAD-RADS CATEGORIES: (based on most severe single lesion)  0: 0%, No stenosis   1: 1-24%, Minimal stenosis  2: 25-49%, Mild stenosis  3: 50-69%, Moderate stenosis  4: 70-99%, Severe stenosis  5: 100%, Occluded    Modifiers:  N: Non-diagnostic segment(s)  S: Stent  G: Graft  V: Vulnerable plaque      IMPRESSION:    1. Left main and three vessel predominantly calcified coronary artery disease.  Coronary calcium score is 3278. CAD RADS N. Alternative cardiac testing should  be considered.  2. Negative for thoracic aortic aneurysm, intramural hematoma, dissection, and  penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer. Minimal thoracic aortic calcified  atherosclerotic plaque.  3. Negative for acute pulmonary embolism.  4. Nonspecific nodular noncavitary pulmonary consolidation in the right upper  lobe and multifocal and bilateral pulmonary micronodularity greatest in the  right upper lobe. Consider atypical infection and drug toxicity.  5. Trace bilateral pleural and pericardial simple effusions.  6. Bulky inferior cervical and thoracic lymphadenopathy consistent with clinical  history of CLL.  7. Indeterminate osseous sclerotic lesion in the left glenoid. No associated  soft tissue mass or pathologic fracture.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST   Including 3-D image postprocessing.    COMPARISON: None    TECHNIQUE AND QUALITY:  Acquisition mode: Prospective ECG triggering  Contrast type and volume: Iohexol 350 mg iodine/mL 70 mL  Medication used: Nitroglycerin 800 mcg SL, Metoprolol 5mg IV  Complications: None  Image quality: Good signal noise. No significant artifacts.   Scanner: Aquilion ONE ViSION    FINDINGS:  Coronary Calcium (Agatston unit):   LM: 0  RCA: 59.3  LAD: 300  LCX: 18.4  TOTAL: 378  Percentile age/gender cohort: 82 percentile for age, gender, and  race/ethnicity-matched group per MESA database.    Cardiovascular Angiography:  Large ascending aortic pseudoaneurysm with organizing thrombus measured at  maximum 7.8 cm in diameter.  Proximal intimal tear/dissection is  posterior-superiorly adjacent to the left main ostium.  Maximum diameter of the  tear is measured at 4.9 mm.  A more distal intimal tear/dissection is localized  in the right posterior wall of the mid ascending aorta and measured at maximum 7  mm in diameter.  The pseudoaneurysm compresses on the right pulmonary artery,  causing severe slit-like narrowing.  In addition, there is a fistula  communicating between the pseudoaneurysm and the right pulmonary artery with  maximum diameter measured at 5.6 mm.    Bileaflet mechanical prosthesis in aortic valve position. Both leaflets in  closing position.  No thrombus identified on or near the leaflets.  Small (<5  mm) hypo-enhancing density is seen below the left-anterior segment of the lower  sewing ring in the LVOT.  Small, hemodynamically insignificant thrombus is  suspected.  Dual-chamber pacemaker leads identified in right atrium and right  ventricle.  The tip of the RV lead is localized in the RV apex.  The tip of the  RA lead is on the interatrial septum.  No evidence of left to right interatrial  shunt.    No evidence of thrombus in the left atrium and left atrial appendage.  Normally  connected right and left pulmonary veins.  Right pulmonary venous return appears  less opacified than left pulmonary venous return.  Normally connected coronary  sinus, superior and inferior vena cava.  No pericardial effusion.    Coronary Angiography:  1) Left main:  Widely patent.  2) Left anterior descending (LAD):  Multifocal calcified and noncalcified  plaques in the proximal and mid segments.  Mild nonobstructive atherosclerosis  in the proximal segment (25-49% stenosis).  Intermediate atherosclerosis in the  mid segment (45-55% stenosis).  Due to indeterminate atherosclerotic disease in  the mid segment, study is submitted for CT FFR analysis.  3) Right coronary artery (RCA):  The ostium of the right coronary artery is  widely patent. Probable subpleural lymph nodes along  the fissures (images 7 on the left, image 31 on the right) are stable since  PET/CT 06/23/2014. Mild bibasal scarring/atelectasis. CT_report: EXAM:  CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: High risk of coronary disease    TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed prior to the administration of  intravenous contrast using prospective ECG gating and reconstruction of  contiguous axial images through the heart during diastole. Postprocessing was  performed on an independent 3D workstation in order to calculate the patient's  calcium score according to the Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.  Subsequently, Intravenous contrast was administered and a CT of the heart was  done with prospective ECG gating during a single breath-held acquisition. A  diastolic-phase axial thin slice (>1mm) reconstruction was performed and sent to  an independent workstation for further processing. Iodinated contrast was  administered intravenously; see the patient's electronic medical record for the  amount and type of contrast administered and wasted. Premedication with  Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol. 3-D  reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating  oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an  independent 3-D workstation.      CORONARY FINDINGS: The patient has normal coronary anatomy. Coronary circulation  is Right dominant.    Calcium Score: Left main = zero; Left anterior descending = zero; Circumflex =  zero; Right =zero  Total score: zero    Left main coronary artery: Normal, no disease; no stenosis.    Left anterior descending coronary artery system: Normal with normal diagonal  branches, no disease; no stenosis.    Left circumflex coronary artery: Normal with normal obtuse marginal branches, no  disease; no stenosis.    Right coronary artery: Normal with normal posterior descending branch, no  disease; no stenosis. CT_report: Indications: Unspecified retinal disorder;Other hypertrophic cardiomyopathy;HCM   ORIGINAL REPORT - 04-Jan-2018 16:44:00   CT Angio Coronary   IMPRESSION:   1. Three-vessel coronary atherosclerotic disease with areas of moderate mid left anterior descending coronary artery, moderate mid to distal left circumflex coronary artery, and severe proximal to mid right coronary artery narrowing. The right coronary artery severe narrowing is caused by low-attenuation plaque with exoenteric dilatation of the vessel suggesting high risk plaque morphology. Overall there is extensive calcified plaque which extends into multiple branch vessels limiting ability to quantify branch vessel stenosis. Consider cardiac catheterization or perfusion imaging.   2. Left ventricular thickening somewhat asymmetric to the basilar interventricular septum in keeping with history of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. Abnormal anterior medial positioning of the thickened anterior papillary muscle causes mid ventricular narrowing.   3. Marked dilatation of the main pulmonary artery without significant central pulmonary artery dilatation possibly idiopathic.   4. Likely patent foramen ovale.      HISTORY: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy; chest pain      HEART AND CORONARY ARTERIES ANGIO CT TECHNIQUE: ECG gated 3D short, vertical long, and horizontal long axis maximum intensity projections; 3D volume renderings; and curved reformats performed to better evaluate coronary arteries. Iodinated contrast media administered intravenously; see PowerChart for the amounts and type of iodinated contrast media administered and wasted.      COMPARISON: None      FINDINGS:   Coronary calcium score 1799      Coronary artery circulation is left coronary dominant with the left circumflex coronary artery supplying the posterior lateral ventricular branch as well as the posterior descending coronary artery. There are normal origins and courses.      The right coronary artery is a diminutive vessel with patchy areas of calcified plaque throughout the proximal segment without evidence of severe narrowing. At the junction of the proximal and middle segments there is a low-attenuation minimally calcified centrally plaque that causes severe stenosis as well as some exhalatory dilatation of the artery focally. The distal vessel remains patent but diminutive with areas of focal calcified plaque. Right ventricular outflow tract and sinoatrial nodal branch is arise from the right coronary artery and are patent.      Large posterior superior calcified plaque within the short left main coronary artery is seen with only mild narrowing (less than 25% luminal narrowing). There is extensive calcified plaque throughout the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery causing only mild appreciable narrowing allowing for the limitations of the extensive calcium. There is extensive calcified plaque within the mid left anterior descending coronary artery with an area of moderate luminal narrowing just proximal to the takeoff of the second diagonal branch. After this point the left anterior descending coronary artery becomes intramural over a very long course throughout the remainder of the segment but remains patent extending to the left ventricular apex as a patent vessel. The first diagonal branch is a tiny vessel. The second diagonal branch has extensive areas of calcification proximally with the vessel to small in caliber to adequately evaluate. The distal vessel does remain patent.      Minimal calcified plaque within the proximal left circumflex coronary artery without luminal narrowing. Patchy areas of calcified plaque throughout the mid and distal left circumflex coronary artery are seen with an area of moderate narrowing just proximal to the takeoff of a third obtuse marginal branch due to calcified plaque. Calcified plaque extends into the distal left circumflex coronary artery with areas of mild to moderate narrowing. The posterior descending coronary artery is a branch to small to adequately characterize with extensive calcified plaque but is patent with contrast seen distally. Proximal first obtuse marginal branch has extensive areas of calcification but is patent and too small to adequately characterize degree of stenosis. Second obtuse marginal branch is tiny and diminutive without calcification. Third obtuse marginal branch displays patchy areas of calcification throughout but is a patent vessel. Posterior lateral ventricular branch is patent but diminutive.      Minimal calcification and thickening of the aortic valve leaflets. Thoracic aorta is normal in caliber. Left transvenous pacer fibrillator with right atrial and right ventricular leads is in place. Concentric hypertrophy somewhat asymmetric to the interventricular septum is seen with thickening also seen in the papillary muscles. The anterior papillary muscle is slightly anteriorly and medially displaced resulting in mid ventricular narrowing proximal to the left ventricular outflow tract. No pericardial effusion. There is marked enlargement of the main pulmonary artery measuring 46 mm in diameter. Right and left pulmonary arteries are normal in caliber and the mitral valve itself does not appear significantly thickened. This may reflect idiopathic dilatation of the pulmonary artery.      There is separation of membranes at the fossa ovalis in keeping with a patent foramen ovale.      Subcentimeter left periaortic nodes at image 2 are noted likely reactive. Limited visualization upper abdomen normal. No osseous lesion.      No consolidation, pleural effusion or pneumothorax.      Electronically signed by:    Kristopher Cummings, M.D. 04-Jan-2018 16:44

The distal vessel does remain patent.      Minimal calcified plaque within the proximal left circumflex coronary artery without luminal narrowing. Patchy areas of calcified plaque throughout the mid and distal left circumflex coronary artery are seen with an area of moderate narrowing just proximal to the takeoff of a third obtuse marginal branch due to calcified plaque. Calcified plaque extends into the distal left circumflex coronary artery with areas of mild to moderate narrowing. The posterior descending coronary artery is a branch to small to adequately characterize with extensive calcified plaque but is patent with contrast seen distally. Proximal first obtuse marginal branch has extensive areas of calcification but is patent and too small to adequately characterize degree of stenosis. Second obtuse marginal branch is tiny and diminutive without calcification. Third obtuse marginal branch displays patchy areas of calcification throughout but is a patent vessel. Posterior lateral ventricular branch is patent but diminutive.      Minimal calcification and thickening of the aortic valve leaflets. Thoracic aorta is normal in caliber. Left transvenous pacer fibrillator with right atrial and right ventricular leads is in place. Concentric hypertrophy somewhat asymmetric to the interventricular septum is seen with thickening also seen in the papillary muscles. The anterior papillary muscle is slightly anteriorly and medially displaced resulting in mid ventricular narrowing proximal to the left ventricular outflow tract. No pericardial effusion. There is marked enlargement of the main pulmonary artery measuring 46 mm in diameter. Right and left pulmonary arteries are normal in caliber and the mitral valve itself does not appear significantly thickened. This may reflect idiopathic dilatation of the pulmonary artery.      There is separation of membranes at the fossa ovalis in keeping with a patent foramen ovale.      Subcentimeter left periaortic nodes at image 2 are noted likely reactive. Limited visualization upper abdomen normal. No osseous lesion.      No consolidation, pleural effusion or pneumothorax.      Electronically signed by:    Kristopher Cummings, M.D. 04-Jan-2018 16:44

CT_report: Indications: Nonrheumatic aortic (valve) stenosis;CAD and bicuspid AV   ORIGINAL REPORT - 29-Aug-2018 23:51:00   CT Angio Coronary         IMPRESSION: At least moderate three-vessel coronary disease which appears severe in the distal left circumflex distribution as described below. Further characterization with catheterization is recommended, provided that it is clinically warranted.  The degree of stenosis is difficult to accurately predict with this examination due to a combination of blooming artifact from extensive calcified plaque and motion artifact related to a relatively rapid heart rate.      Coronary calcium score: 1092, This is a very high calcium score generally associated with a risk for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac-related death) of up to 10.8 times patients with 0 calcium scores.      Typed 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with mild aortic stenosis by planimetry, opening area of the aortic valve approximately 2.2 sq cm. No associated aortic disease, no aneurysm or coarctation. Thoracic aorta appears normal.         CLINICAL HISTORY: Aortic valve disease, bicuspid valve, evaluate aorta, also evaluate coronary arteries.         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.  Images were postprocessed on an independent 3-D workstation in order to calculate the patient's calcium score.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a retrospectively R-wave triggered helical cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at multiple phases of the R-R interval.  Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an independent 3-D workstation.      Premedication with Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.         COMPARE: No prior studies are available for comparison.         VASCULAR FINDINGS: Right dominant coronary circulation.      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 1092. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 435 , left circumflex 283, and right coronary artery 374.      Left main coronary artery: Normal sized artery, free of significant atherosclerotic disease, no significant stenosis.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: Several large calcified plaque scattered throughout the left anterior descending coronary artery. There is circumferential calcified plaque at the origin of the LAD appears to cause moderate, between 50 and 70%, loss of luminal diameter. Large calcified plaque in the distal LAD associated with positive remodeling also appears to cause moderate, between 50% and 70%, loss of diameter. LAD gives off several small diagonal and circumflex perforator branches.      Right coronary artery: A large vessel, within the distal aspect of the proximal and proximal aspect of the mid right coronary artery there is extensive calcified plaque and positive remodeling. Evaluation of this vessel is degraded by motion artifact related to the patient's relatively rapid heart rate, suspect that there is at least moderate (50-70% loss of diameter) disease in this region.      Left circumflex coronary artery: A normal-sized vessel. Some eccentric calcified plaque at the origin of the left circumflex appears to cause mild, slightly less than 50%, loss of luminal diameter. Within the distal left circumflex there is a long, irregular, calcified plaque extending over 2.3 cm in vessel associated with some positive remodeling. There appears to be at least moderate and probably severe, greater than 70%, loss of diameter.      There is a type 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with thickened and calcified raphe between the right and left sinuses of Valsalva. The leaflets are moderately to severely thickened with a moderate to severe amount of associated calcification which does not appear to extend into the annulus. By planimetry, the opening area of the bowel is approximately 2.2 sq cm. The annulus is 28 x 23 mm, sinuses of Valsalva measuring 38 x 34 mm, sinotubular junction measures 30 x 29 mm, tubular ascending aorta measures up to 35 x 34 mm.      Left ventricle appears normal in size and systolic function, estimated ejection fraction is greater than 70%. No focal wall motion abnormalities are seen. End-diastolic volume approximately 190 mL, end-systolic volume approximately 50 mL, stroke volume approximately 140 mL. There is borderline concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, left ventricular wall measures up to 12 mm in thickness. There is mild mitral valve prolapse in the left atrium is enlarged. Qualitatively, right ventricular size and systolic function appear normal.      Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber, no acute aortic pathology. No aneurysm or coarctation. Central pulmonary arteries are normal in appearance, no large central pulmonary emboli are seen.         NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Mild upper lobe predominant centrilobular and paraseptal emphysematous changes. Some calcified nodules in the right lower lobe are consistent with old granulomatous disease. No significant edema, effusion, or pneumothorax, no pneumonia.      No significant pericardial effusion is seen. No thoracic lymphadenopathy. Calcified right hilar lymph nodes are consistent with old granulomatous disease.  Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen demonstrates stigmata of cirrhosis and portal hypertension with TIPS, splenomegaly, varices, postembolization changes left upper quadrant. No acute appearing fractures or dislocations.                  Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 29-Aug-2018 23:51

CT_report: Indications: Unspecified systolic (congestive) heart failure;eval for coronary-PA fistula based on abnormal echo   ORIGINAL REPORT - 24-Jan-2018 17:50:00   CT Angio Coronary         IMPRESSION: No findings to suggest any significant coronary artery to pulmonary artery fistula or shunting.      Coronary arteries appear normal, patient's heart failure likely related to nonischemic cardiomyopathy.      Coronary calcium score: 0         CLINICAL HISTORY: Findings on recent echocardiogram suspicious for coronary to pulmonary artery fistula. Patient has unspecified systolic heart failure.         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.  Images were postprocessed on an independent 3-D workstation in order to calculate the patient's calcium score.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a prospectively R-wave triggered step-and-shoot cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 70% of the R-R interval.    The entire chest was included in the scan volume. Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an independent 3-D workstation.         COMPARE: Echocardiogram performed 1/8/2018 is available for comparison.         FINDINGS: The patient has a codominant coronary circulation.      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 0. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 0 , left circumflex 0, and right coronary artery 0.      Left main coronary artery: Normal sized artery, no significant atherosclerotic disease, no stenosis.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: Normal sized artery giving rise to prominent first and second diagonal branches. The mid to distal LAD is relatively small, wraps around the cardiac apex. No significant atherosclerotic disease, no stenosis.      Right coronary artery: The right coronary artery is a small vessel, evaluation is somewhat degraded by artifact. The right coronary artery gives rise to the SA nodal branch, gives off normal-appearing acute marginal and small posterior descending artery branches.      Left circumflex coronary artery: A normal size artery with normal-appearing kidneys marginal branches. A small ramus intermedius branch is also noted.      No findings to suggest fistulization between the left coronary circulation and a left pulmonary artery branch. The main pulmonary artery upper limits of normal in size, 30 mm in diameter. Left atrial appendage is well opacified with contrast, no thrombus is seen. Same can be said for right atrial appendage. 4 pulmonary veins, no partial anomalous pulmonary venous return. Pulmonary veins are dilated consistent with history of systolic left ventricular failure. The heart appears mildly enlarged, no definite septal defects. Atrial level shunting seen on recent echo probably related to patent foramen ovale as there are no findings to suggest an atrial septal defect.      Prominent cardiac fat pad. Heart upper limits of normal in size. No pericardial effusion. A small hiatal hernia noted. No significant thoracic lymphadenopathy. Left-sided 3 vessel aortic arch, tortuous arch vessels. Thyroid gland appears mildly enlarged with multiple nodules which are difficult to further characterize given the early phase of contrast administration.      Elevation of the right hemidiaphragm. Suspect some mild hepatic steatosis. Some degenerative disc disease noted. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions, no acute-appearing fractures. Somewhat expiratory technique with flattening of the posterior membrane of the trachea, dependent atelectasis, and areas of decreased attenuation within the lungs consistent with some underlying airways disease, air trapping. Some increased density in the perihilar regions likely reflecting some mild underlying pulmonary edema. No findings to suggest pneumonia. Small benign calcified granulomas noted within lung bases. No pleural effusion, no pneumothorax.      Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 24-Jan-2018 17:50*** APPENDED REPORT *** - 30-Jan-2018 12:48:00   CT Angio Coronary:      3D axial maximum intensity projections performed to better evaluate vasculature.         Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 30-Jan-2018 12:48

if unchanged then CT at 18-24 months   >8mm         Consider follow-up CT at 3 months, PET-CT, tissue sampling or  Pulmonary Med consultation for management    For multiple nodules, size* of largest or most suspicious nodule:  <6mm          No routine follow-up required  6mm    CT at 3-6 months; CT_report: Indications: Shortness of breath;SOB/?Pulmonary Fibrosis   ORIGINAL REPORT - 27-Jan-2016 08:15:00   CT CHEST WO/CST+ d 3D   IMPRESSION:      Mild multifocal peripheral predominant reticulation and traction bronchiectasis consistent with fibrotic lung disease. The findings are probably mildly basal predominant. No clear convincing evidence of honeycombing. The findings are consistent with "probable"usual interstitial pneumonia/idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, possibly some age-related parenchymal changes as well. Given the absence of honeycombing and the usual more pronounced course appearance of usual interstitial pneumonia, that diagnosis cannot be considered definite. The findings have progressed some compared to the visualized portions lung parenchymal 9/20/2005      CLINICAL HISTORY: Shorts of breath and fibrosis.      TECHNIQUE: High resolution 1 mm images at 3 mm intervals and contiguous 3 mm images were reconstructed through the chest.  No intravenous contrast was used.  Images were reformatted in the coronal plane to better assess distribution and extent of suspected interstitial abnormalities. Selected high resolution 1 mm images were also performed at end-expiration and in the prone position to better assess for possible interstitial lung disease.  3D post-processing tools were applied as needed to the raw data set to better depict and clarify relevant findings.      Compare: Prior coronary calcium score recent radiograph.      Mediastinum: No mediastinal or hilar lymph node enlargement No pericardial abnormality. Aortic valvular calcium and coronary artery calcium. Calcified right peribronchial and mediastinal lymph nodes. Ectasia ascending aorta level main pulmonary artery image 58 45-mm. Main pulmonary artery at this level measures about 32 mm, consistent with mild dilation. Prominent upper normal subaortic left periesophageal and right paratracheal and azygoesophageal recess lymph nodes.      Pleura: No significant pleural abnormality.      Abdomen: Calcified granulomas liver and spleen and cholecystectomy.  Please see dedicated report.      Lungs:    . Patchy bilateral subpleural very fine reticulation, probably with some mild bronchiolectasis in the right greater left base is best visualized on prone imaging, with minimal subpleural cystic change as well. Mild architectural distortion is present    .     .      Chest Wall: No lymphadenopathy.     .         Electronically signed by:    Gotway, Michael B. M.D. 27-Jan-2016 08:15

Tortuous aorta with ectasia of the arch and descending aorta, increased since the prior exam. Mild bibasilar atelectasis or scarring. Old left rib fracture. Chest otherwise negative.      Electronically signed by:    A Madhavan MD 127-13730 05-Sep-2017 10:54        D. White MD 4-6304 05-Sep-2017 10:54
CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification  scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial  reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation  in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: Abdominopelvic CT, 9/5/2017    FINDINGS:      Score:  Left main coronary artery: zero    Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero    Circumflex coronary artery: zero    Right coronary artery: zero      Total score: zero       ADDITIONAL FINDINGS: There is a 13 x 10 mm nodular density in the peripheral  aspect of the left lower lobe abutting the chest wall, series 4 image 59, which  appears solid and noncalcified. Nodule has irregular margins and I suspect some  peripheral consolidation architectural distortion, see series 4 image 57.  Finding is directly adjacent to a small focus of abdominal fat which herniates  into the left lateral costophrenic angle throughout small diaphragmatic defect.  I suspect that the adjacent pulmonary finding represents some chronic scarring  and associated atelectasis which was present to some extent on the prior CT  performed 9/5/2017 and appears slightly more prominent today, probably of no  clinical consequence. Otherwise, visualized portions of the lungs are clear.    Fusiform aneurysmal dilatation of ascending aorta up to 45 mm, mild. This  relative dilatation of the proximal descending thoracic aorta up to 39 mm. No  pericardial thickening or pericardial effusion. Limited evaluation of the upper  abdomen demonstrates partially imaged mild splenomegaly. Some thickening of the  lower esophagus noted perhaps suggesting some reflux esophagitis. No lytic or  blastic osseous lesions are seen.    IMPRESSION:  Coronary artery calcium score of zero. 36% of patients in an age,  gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary  calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative  predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac  related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.    Mild fusiform aneurysmal dilatation of the ascending aorta up to 45 mm, amenable  to continued attention on any future CT scanning.    Mild thickening of the lower esophagus probably in part related to a tiny  sliding hiatal hernia. If the patient is having any symptoms of gastroesophageal  reflux and has not had an upper endoscopy, such an examination helpful to  evaluate for any underlying mucosal changes.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification scoring  protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent 3D workstation as ordered by the treating  provider and reviewed by the radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according  to the Agatston-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: CT CorCal 4/25/2013    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 0  Percentile rank: 0 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for coronary artery disease  with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex is 68%. High density seen along  the mid LAD does not meet the Agatston threshold for calcific plaque.     OTHER FINDINGS: Multiple sub-3 mm bilateral pulmonary nodules, some of which are calcified. Based on  size criteria these are likely benign. . A poorly defined groundglass nodule in the left lower lobe  measures 8 mm (series 4, image 15) and was not confidently identified on the prior scan from 2013.  Mild degenerative change of the thoracic spine.     RECOMMENDATIONS FOR MANAGEMENT OF SUBSOLID (includes ground glass and part-solid) PULMONARY NODULES  DETECTED AT CT.    SOLITARY PURE GROUND GLASS NODULES (GGNs):  Single nodule size (mm) *:     <6mm No routine CT follow-up required*  6mm or > CT at 6-12 months. If persistent, then CT every 2 years until stable for 5 years.  FDG PET  is not recommended.    *In certain suspicious nodules <6mm, consider follow-up at 2 and 4 years.  If there is growth or  solid component develops, consider resection.    #Persistent part-solid nodules with solid components 6mm or > should be considered highly  suspicious.  ~Multiple <6mm pure ground glass nodules are usually benign, but consider follow-up at 2 and 4  years in selected patients at high risk.      IMPRESSION:  1. Observed coronary calcium score is 0. For comparison purposes, the estimated probability of a  non-zero calcium score for a group of patients asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the  same age, race/ethnicity and sex is 68%.  2. 8 mm groundglass nodule in the left lower lobe appears new compared to 2013. Imaging follow-up is  suggested in 6-12 months to assess for interval change. Detailed imaging follow-up guidelines are  provided in the body of the report.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery  calcification scoring protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent  3D workstation as ordered by the treating provider and reviewed by the  radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatston-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 0    OTHER FINDINGS: A few pulmonary nodules measure 4 mm or less in mean diameter,  specifically in the right middle lobe (4/64), right lower lobe (4/60), and left  lower lobe (4/41). Calcified left hilar lymph nodes.       GUIDELINES FOR FOLLOW-UP of newly detected solid nodules incidentally detected  on CT in persons 35 years or older. (2017 revision)    LOW-RISK PATIENT (Minimal or absent history of smoking or of other known risk  factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then consider CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm  Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with  CT at 3 months    For multiple nodules, size of largest nodule:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6mm or > CT at 3-6 months, then consider CT at 18-24 months      HIGH-RISK PATIENT (History of smoking or of other known risk factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with  CT at 3 months    For multiple nodules, size of largest nodule:  <6mm Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6mm or > CT at 3-6 months, then at 18-24 months    (Nodule size is the average of length and width.)    *Nodules <6mm do not require routine follow-up, but certain patients at high  risk with suspicious nodule morphology, upper lobe location, or both may warrant  12-month follow-up.      Guidelines do not apply to lung cancer screening, patients with  immunosuppression, or patients with a known primary cancer.      IMPRESSION:  1.  The observed coronary calcium score is 0.  2.  Scattered pulmonary nodules measuring up to 4 mm for which follow-up  considerations have been provided.

CT_report: Indications: PRIM CARDIOMYOPATHY NEC;   ORIGINAL REPORT - 14-Jun-2010 14:22:00   CT Angio Coronary:      IMPRESSION:   #1. Significant coronary artery atherosclerosis is present with a focal stenosis between 50 and 70% in the mid left anterior descending artery caused a largely by ecentric noncalcified plaque. There also may be areas of stenosis in the mid right coronary artery although assessment is limited as above.      Technique: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous 2.5 mm axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval. Subsequently, intravenous contrast was administered and a prospectively R-wave triggered step-and-shoot cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 70% of the R-R interval. The source 0.625 axial images were transferred to the Advantage Windows workstation for real-time multiplanar reformatting. Short and long axis views and rotating oblique reformatted views were also performed of the coronary arteries.      Premedication with Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.      Contrast: 110 mL Visipaque 320.      FINDINGS: The exam is somewhat noise limited due to the size of the patient. The coronary calcium score is 778. This places the patient in the 93rd percentile based on comparison to age and sex matched controls. A dual-lead pacemaker is in place.      Following intravenous contrast there is fair opacification of the coronary arterial system, which is right dominant. The left main coronary artery is patent without plaque or stenosis. The LAD contains mixed calcified and noncalcified plaque in its midportion immediately distal to the origin of the first diagonal which is a prominent vessel. The mixed plaque distal to the first diagonal causes a stenosis apparently between 50 and 70%. Distally the second diagonal appears patent. The distal LAD also appears patent with a short shallow segment of tunneling in the myocardium. The LAD tapers at the cardiac apex and is a very small vessel. The large first diagonal contains abundant calcified plaque without a definite stenosis. The second diagonal also is patent.      The left circumflex coronary artery contains mixed calcified and noncalcified plaque particularly in its proximal portion and gives rise to a marginal branch. It also gives rise to a posterior ventricular branch at the cardiac base. The right coronary artery is poorly opacified and very small. It contains a significant calcified and noncalcified plaque in its midportion proximal to the origin of a marginal branch. There is also disease more distally in the RCA. The posterior descending artery is patent. There are several areas in which calcification and the associated blooming artifact limit assessment of the lumen of the small right coronary particularly in its midportion.      The cardiac chambers are grossly normal in size. The aortic valve is tricuspid and is not calcified. Visualized lungs are clear.      IMPRESSION:   #1. Significant coronary artery atherosclerosis is present with a focal stenosis between 50 and 70% in the mid left anterior descending artery caused a largely by ecentric noncalcified plaque. There also may be areas of stenosis in the mid right coronary artery although assessment is limited as above. Iodinated contrast media administered intravenously; see PowerChart for the amounts and type of iodinated contrast media administered and wasted.      COMPARISON: None      FINDINGS:   Coronary calcium score is 0.      Coronary arterial system is right heart dominant. There are normal coronary origins and courses.      Left main coronary artery is widely patent without atherosclerotic disease. Left anterior descending coronary artery is mildly tortuous in its mid and distal aspects but is widely patent without evidence of stenosis. 2 diagonal vessels are seen which are widely patent though tortuous. The left circumflex coronary artery is widely patent an gives rise to 2 obtuse marginal branches that are widely patent without evidence of stenosis. The right coronary artery has no stenosis in the right posterior lateral ventricular branch and posterior descending coronary arteries opacify normally as does an acute marginal branch.      The ascending aorta is normal in caliber measuring 37 mm at the sinuses of Valsalva 28 mm at the sinotubular junction and 34 mm in the mid ascending aorta area      Heart is normal in size without pericardial effusion. Calcified mediastinal and right hilar nodes are in keeping with healed granulomatous disease.      Small hiatal hernia is noted. Segment 4A hepatic cyst is noted. No osseous lesion is seen. No consolidation, pleural effusion or pneumothorax.         Electronically signed by:    Kristopher Cummings, M.D. 01-Feb-2016 14:44

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: None    TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification  scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial  reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation  in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:      Score:  Left main coronary artery: zero    Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero    Circumflex coronary artery: zero    Right coronary artery: zero      Total score: zero       INCIDENTAL FINDINGS: Peripheral and lower lung predominant  centrilobular/tree-in-bud nodules some of which are calcified. There is  associated architectural distortion. No significant associated bronchiectasis,  no pleural effusion or pneumothorax. No adenopathy within visualized portions of  the lower chest and upper abdomen. Visualized portions of the upper abdomen are  unremarkable. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen.    IMPRESSION:  Coronary artery calcium score of zero. 47% of patients in an age,  gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary  calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative  predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac  related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.    Nodularity in the lower lungs in a pattern most consistent with some dendriform  pulmonary ossification, benign.

CT_report: Indications: Nonrheumatic mitral (valve) insufficiency;Preop Minimally Invasive Mitral valve repair/ size of vessels   ORIGINAL REPORT - 21-Aug-2017 17:47:00         IMPRESSION:   No significant coronary artery stenosis or plaque.      Mitral valve anatomy as described below.      Coronary calcium score: 0         CLINICAL HISTORY: Nontraumatic mitral valve insufficiency. Preoperative         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 71 % of the R-R interval.         Intravenous contrast was administered and a retrospective R-wave triggered acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 20 and 78 % of the R-R interval.  Theaxial images were transferred to a 3-D workstation for multiplanar and 3-D reformatting. Short and long axis views and rotating oblique reformatted views were also performed of the coronary arteries. Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      Premedication with Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.         COMPARE: No prior studies are available for comparison.         VASCULAR FINDINGS:      No significant atherosclerotic disease noted within the aorta are its branches. The right subclavian artery measures 10 mm in diameter near the origin. The left subclavian artery measures 9 mm in diameter (images 115, 128)..      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 0. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 0 , left circumflex 0, and right coronary artery 0.      Left main coronary artery: Normal origin of the left main from the left coronary cusp and bifurcation into LAD and circumflex.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: Small caliber LAD, with smaller septal and diagonal branches, without significant stenosis or plaque.      Right coronary artery: Normal origin of the right coronary from the right coronary cusp. Small caliber acute marginal branch, with the posterior descending arising from the right coronary. No significant coronary artery stenosis or plaque.      Left circumflex coronary artery: No significant stenosis or plaque in the circumflex distribution. The heart is normal in size. Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber, no acute aortic pathology. Central pulmonary arteries are normal in appearance, no large central pulmonary emboli are seen.      Mild thickening of the anterior and posterior mitral valve leaflets. Significant prolapse of posterior mitral valve leaflet into the left atrium (image 283, series 13). Minimal calcification of the mitral annulus along the septal region (image 49, series 4).         NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Calcified granuloma left lung apex. Scarring in the lung apices. Otherwise, The lungs are clear. No pleural effusion, no pneumothorax. No thoracic lymphadenopathy. Visualized portions of the upper abdomen are unremarkable. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen..      For right adrenal lesion and description of abdominal findings, please refer to separate CT angiogram abdomen and pelvis report from same day.                  Electronically signed by:    P. Panse, M.D. 21-Aug-2017 17:47

CT_report: Indications: Nonrheumatic aortic (valve) stenosis;CAD and bicuspid AV   ORIGINAL REPORT - 29-Aug-2018 23:51:00   CT Angio Coronary         IMPRESSION: At least moderate three-vessel coronary disease which appears severe in the distal left circumflex distribution as described below. Further characterization with catheterization is recommended, provided that it is clinically warranted.  The degree of stenosis is difficult to accurately predict with this examination due to a combination of blooming artifact from extensive calcified plaque and motion artifact related to a relatively rapid heart rate.      Coronary calcium score: 1092, This is a very high calcium score generally associated with a risk for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac-related death) of up to 10.8 times patients with 0 calcium scores.      Typed 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with mild aortic stenosis by planimetry, opening area of the aortic valve approximately 2.2 sq cm. No associated aortic disease, no aneurysm or coarctation. Thoracic aorta appears normal.         CLINICAL HISTORY: Aortic valve disease, bicuspid valve, evaluate aorta, also evaluate coronary arteries.         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.  Images were postprocessed on an independent 3-D workstation in order to calculate the patient's calcium score.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a retrospectively R-wave triggered helical cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at multiple phases of the R-R interval.  Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an independent 3-D workstation.      Premedication with Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.         COMPARE: No prior studies are available for comparison.         VASCULAR FINDINGS: Right dominant coronary circulation.      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 1092. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 435 , left circumflex 283, and right coronary artery 374.      Left main coronary artery: Normal sized artery, free of significant atherosclerotic disease, no significant stenosis.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: Several large calcified plaque scattered throughout the left anterior descending coronary artery. There is circumferential calcified plaque at the origin of the LAD appears to cause moderate, between 50 and 70%, loss of luminal diameter. Large calcified plaque in the distal LAD associated with positive remodeling also appears to cause moderate, between 50% and 70%, loss of diameter. LAD gives off several small diagonal and circumflex perforator branches.      Right coronary artery: A large vessel, within the distal aspect of the proximal and proximal aspect of the mid right coronary artery there is extensive calcified plaque and positive remodeling. Evaluation of this vessel is degraded by motion artifact related to the patient's relatively rapid heart rate, suspect that there is at least moderate (50-70% loss of diameter) disease in this region.      Left circumflex coronary artery: A normal-sized vessel. Some eccentric calcified plaque at the origin of the left circumflex appears to cause mild, slightly less than 50%, loss of luminal diameter. Within the distal left circumflex there is a long, irregular, calcified plaque extending over 2.3 cm in vessel associated with some positive remodeling. There appears to be at least moderate and probably severe, greater than 70%, loss of diameter.      There is a type 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with thickened and calcified raphe between the right and left sinuses of Valsalva. The leaflets are moderately to severely thickened with a moderate to severe amount of associated calcification which does not appear to extend into the annulus. By planimetry, the opening area of the bowel is approximately 2.2 sq cm. The annulus is 28 x 23 mm, sinuses of Valsalva measuring 38 x 34 mm, sinotubular junction measures 30 x 29 mm, tubular ascending aorta measures up to 35 x 34 mm.      Left ventricle appears normal in size and systolic function, estimated ejection fraction is greater than 70%. No focal wall motion abnormalities are seen. End-diastolic volume approximately 190 mL, end-systolic volume approximately 50 mL, stroke volume approximately 140 mL. There is borderline concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, left ventricular wall measures up to 12 mm in thickness. There is mild mitral valve prolapse in the left atrium is enlarged. Qualitatively, right ventricular size and systolic function appear normal.      Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber, no acute aortic pathology. No aneurysm or coarctation. Central pulmonary arteries are normal in appearance, no large central pulmonary emboli are seen.         NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Mild upper lobe predominant centrilobular and paraseptal emphysematous changes. Some calcified nodules in the right lower lobe are consistent with old granulomatous disease. No significant edema, effusion, or pneumothorax, no pneumonia.      No significant pericardial effusion is seen. No thoracic lymphadenopathy. Calcified right hilar lymph nodes are consistent with old granulomatous disease.  Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen demonstrates stigmata of cirrhosis and portal hypertension with TIPS, splenomegaly, varices, postembolization changes left upper quadrant. No acute appearing fractures or dislocations.                  Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 29-Aug-2018 23:51

There is circumferential calcified plaque at the origin of the LAD appears to cause moderate, between 50 and 70%, loss of luminal diameter. Large calcified plaque in the distal LAD associated with positive remodeling also appears to cause moderate, between 50% and 70%, loss of diameter. LAD gives off several small diagonal and circumflex perforator branches.      Right coronary artery: A large vessel, within the distal aspect of the proximal and proximal aspect of the mid right coronary artery there is extensive calcified plaque and positive remodeling. Evaluation of this vessel is degraded by motion artifact related to the patient's relatively rapid heart rate, suspect that there is at least moderate (50-70% loss of diameter) disease in this region.      Left circumflex coronary artery: A normal-sized vessel. Some eccentric calcified plaque at the origin of the left circumflex appears to cause mild, slightly less than 50%, loss of luminal diameter. Within the distal left circumflex there is a long, irregular, calcified plaque extending over 2.3 cm in vessel associated with some positive remodeling. There appears to be at least moderate and probably severe, greater than 70%, loss of diameter.      There is a type 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with thickened and calcified raphe between the right and left sinuses of Valsalva. The leaflets are moderately to severely thickened with a moderate to severe amount of associated calcification which does not appear to extend into the annulus. By planimetry, the opening area of the bowel is approximately 2.2 sq cm. The annulus is 28 x 23 mm, sinuses of Valsalva measuring 38 x 34 mm, sinotubular junction measures 30 x 29 mm, tubular ascending aorta measures up to 35 x 34 mm.      Left ventricle appears normal in size and systolic function, estimated ejection fraction is greater than 70%. No focal wall motion abnormalities are seen. End-diastolic volume approximately 190 mL, end-systolic volume approximately 50 mL, stroke volume approximately 140 mL. There is borderline concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, left ventricular wall measures up to 12 mm in thickness. There is mild mitral valve prolapse in the left atrium is enlarged. Qualitatively, right ventricular size and systolic function appear normal.      Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber, no acute aortic pathology. No aneurysm or coarctation. Central pulmonary arteries are normal in appearance, no large central pulmonary emboli are seen.         NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Mild upper lobe predominant centrilobular and paraseptal emphysematous changes. Some calcified nodules in the right lower lobe are consistent with old granulomatous disease. No significant edema, effusion, or pneumothorax, no pneumonia.      No significant pericardial effusion is seen. No thoracic lymphadenopathy. Calcified right hilar lymph nodes are consistent with old granulomatous disease.  Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen demonstrates stigmata of cirrhosis and portal hypertension with TIPS, splenomegaly, varices, postembolization changes left upper quadrant. No acute appearing fractures or dislocations.                  Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 29-Aug-2018 23:51

Chest_Xray_report: EXAM: DX CHEST PORTABLE 1 VIEW    COMPARISON: Radiographs 7/24/21, 7/23/21.    IMPRESSION:  Postsurgical changes of right lower lobectomy and mediastinal  lymphadenectomy. Unchanged positioning of a right basilar pigtail pleural  drainage catheter. Left PICC tip in the mid SVC. Surgical clips overlying the  hila bilaterally and the right axilla. Single surgical clip in the lateral right  lung base.    Unchanged right hemithorax volume loss with elevation of the right  hemidiaphragm. Improved right basilar pneumothorax with increased attenuation of  the right costophrenic angle possibly related to decreasing gas and increasing  fluid component. The right apical component is not appreciated today. No left  pneumothorax or pleural effusion. No focal consolidation. Bilateral hilar  fullness likely related to lymphadenopathy. Cardiomediastinal silhouette is  stable.

IMPRESSION:  Findings consistent with pulmonary edema.

CT_report:
EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST_x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
ADDITIONAL HISTORY: None_x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification_x000D_
scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial_x000D_
reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation_x000D_
in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the_x000D_
Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
COMPARISON: None_x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
FINDINGS:  _x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
Score:_x000D_
Left main coronary artery: zero  _x000D_
Left anterior descending coronary artery: 1  _x000D_
Circumflex coronary artery: zero  _x000D_
Right coronary artery: 1  _x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
Total score: 2   _x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
INCIDENTAL FINDINGS: Main pulmonary artery is mildly dilated, 33 mm, suggesting_x000D_
some underlying pulmonary hypertension. Partially imaged 2 cm right adrenal_x000D_
nodule is low attenuation most consistent with a benign adrenal adenoma. Finding_x000D_
was better characterized on a CT performed 2/26/2014, described as an adenoma on_x000D_
that exam._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
IMPRESSION: Coronary artery calcium score of 2. 24th percentile compared to age_x000D_
and gender matched controls. This is a low calcium score generally associated_x000D_
with a risk for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac-related_x000D_
death) of up to 1.9 times patients with 0 calcium scores._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
Prominent main pulmonary artery suggestive of some pulmonary hypertension._x000D_

_x000D_

airways disease such as chronic bronchitis or asthma. Some focal emphysematous_x000D_

perhaps reflecting some recent aspiration change. Otherwise, visualized portions_x000D_
of the lungs are clear. A small hiatal hernia is noted as well as some_x000D_
thickening of the lower esophagus suggesting esophagitis. There is thickening of_x000D_
the bronchi more centrally with some scattered calcifications, see series 3_x000D_
image 5 for example. Some mild aneurysmal dilatation of the ascending aorta up_x000D_
to 4 cm noted. No pericardial effusion. Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen_x000D_
demonstrates a small nodule, probably a splenule along the anterior left upper_x000D_
quadrant series 3 image 58. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions, no acute_x000D_
appearing fractures or dislocations. _x000D_

_x000D_
_x000D_

hiatal hernia and thickening of the lower esophagus suggesting reflux_x000D_
esophagitis, favor sequela of aspiration. Correlation with upper endoscopy may_x000D_
be helpful to evaluate for lower esophageal mucosal changes. _x000D_
